  , issuePullRequest = Nothing
  , issueUrl =
      "https://api.github.com/repos/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/issues/362"
  , issueCreatedAt = 2013 (-02) (-18) 21 : 53 : 22 UTC
  , issueBody =
      Just
        "I have the following dataset:\n\n``` javascript\nr.db('test').tableCreate('tv_shows').run()\nr.table('tv_shows').insert([{ name: 'Star Trek TNG', episodes: 178 },\n                            { name: 'Battlestar Galactica', episodes: 75 }]).run()\nr.db('test').tableCreate('characters').run();\nr.table('characters').insert([{ name: 'Worf', show: 'Star Trek TNG' },\n                              { name: 'Data', show: 'Star Trek TNG' },\n                              { name: 'William Adama', show: 'Battlestar Galactica' },\n                              { name: 'Homer Simpson', show: 'The Simpsons' }]).run()\n```\n\nSuppose that for each character I'd like to inject info from a relevant TV show. I can do it like this:\n\n``` javascript\nr.table('characters').map(function (character) {\n  return r.table('tv_shows').filter({ name: character('show') }).nth(0).merge(character);\n}).run()\n```\n\nBut this doesn't work because the inner `filter` occasionally returns empty streams (when there is no corresponding tv show). The obvious solution is to use a branch:\n\n``` javascript\nr.table('characters').map(function (character) {\n  return r.branch(r.table('tv_shows').filter({ name: character('show') }).count().gt(0),\n                  r.table('tv_shows').filter({ name: character('show') }).nth(0),\n                  r.expr({})).merge(character);\n}).run()\n```\n\nBut eww. @neumino suggested a neat trick of appending an empty object:\n\n``` javascript\nr.table('characters').map(function (character) {\n  return r.table('tv_shows').filter({ name: character('show') }).append({}).nth(0).merge(character);\n}).run()\n```\n\nBetter, but still yucky. One option is to make a stream implicitly convertible to an object as follows: `[]` converts to `{}`, `[x]` converts to `x`, and [x, y, [z*]] throws an error (cannot implicitly convert stream with more than one element to object). I like this solution (I think).\n\nAnother option is to have the user do an explicit cast from stream to object using the rules above. I like this less.\n\nWhat do you think?\n"
